ttribute bound to a specific host interface.","markdown":"Incoming container traffic should be bound to a specific host interface \u003cbr\u003e\u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eValue:\u003c/strong\u003e Docker compose file doesn't have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface \u003cbr\u003e\u003cstrong\u003eExcepted value:\u003c/strong\u003e Docker compose file to have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface."},"fullDescription":{"text":"Incoming container traffic should be bound to a specific host interface Value: Docker compose file doesn't have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface Excepted value: Docker compose file to have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Container Traffic Not Bound To Host Interface","id":"Container Traffic Not Bound To Host Interface - 451d79dc-0588-476a-ad03-3c7f0320abb3 [Taken from query_id] (kics)","description":"Incoming container traffic should be bound to a specific host interface Value: Docker compose file doesn't have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface Excepted value: Docker compose file to have 'ports' attribute bound to a specific host interface.","tags":["security","checkmarx","kics"]}},{"id":"Stored Command Argument Injection - 6227086963064089467 (sast)","name":"Stored Command Argument Injection","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"An argument is passed to an external OS command by run at /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py in line 107. This could allow an attacker to attack the external program by injecting malicious arguments into its execution.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject a command or argument to execute into storage, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 122 of /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py, in the get_pr_info_from_github method.\n\n","markdown":"An argument is passed to an external OS command by run at /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py in line 107. This could allow an attacker to attack the external program by injecting malicious arguments into its execution.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject a command or argument to execute into storage, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 122 of /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py, in the get_pr_info_from_github method.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"An argument is passed to an external OS command by run at /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py in line 107. This could allow an attacker to attack the external program by injecting malicious arguments into its execution.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject a command or argument to execute into storage, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 122 of /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py, in the get_pr_info_from_github method.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Stored Command Argument Injection","id":"Stored Command Argument Injection - 6227086963064089467 (sast)","description":"An argument is passed to an external OS command by run at /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py in line 107. This could allow an attacker to attack the external program by injecting malicious arguments into its execution.\n\nThe attacker may be able to inject a command or argument to execute into storage, which is then retrieved by the application with loads, at line 122 of /.github/scripts/find_prs_between_commits.py, in the get_pr_info_from_github method.\n\n","tags":["security","checkmarx","sast"]}},{"id":"CVE-2026-33532 (sca)","name":"Cve202633532","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"yaml is a YAML parser and serialiser for JavaScript. Parsing a YAML document with a version of yaml on the 1.x branch prior to 1.10.3 or on the 2.x branch prior to 2.8.3 may throw a \u0026#34;RangeError\u0026#34; due to a Stack Overflow. The node resolution/composition phase uses recursive function calls without a depth bound. An attacker who can supply YAML for parsing can trigger a `RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded` with a small payload (~210 KB). The `RangeError` is not a `YAMLParseError`, so applications that only catch YAML-specific errors will encounter an unexpected exception type. Depending on the host application\u0026#39;s exception handling, this can fail requests or terminate the Node.js process. Flow sequences allow deep nesting with minimal bytes (2 bytes per level: one `[` and one `]`). On the default Node.js stack, approximately 1,0005,000 levels of nesting (210 KB input) exhaust the call stack. The exact threshold is environment-dependent (Node.js version, stack size, call stack depth at invocation). Note: the library\u0026#39;s `Parser` (CST phase) uses a stack-based iterative approach and is not affected. Only the compose/resolve phase uses actual call-stack recursion. All three public parsing APIs are affected: `YAML.parse()`, `YAML.parseDocument()`, and `YAML.parseAllDocuments()`. Versions 1.10.3 and 2.8.3 contain a patch.","markdown":"yaml is a YAML parser and serialiser for JavaScript. Parsing a YAML document with a version of yaml on the 1.x branch prior to 1.10.3 or on the 2.x branch prior to 2.8.3 may throw a \u0026#34;RangeError\u0026#34; due to a Stack Overflow. The node resolution/composition phase uses recursive function calls without a depth bound. An attacker who can supply YAML for parsing can trigger a `RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded` with a small payload (~210 KB). The `RangeError` is not a `YAMLParseError`, so applications that only catch YAML-specific errors will encounter an unexpected exception type. Depending on the host application\u0026#39;s exception handling, this can fail requests or terminate the Node.js process. Flow sequences allow deep nesting with minimal bytes (2 bytes per level: one `[` and one `]`). On the default Node.js stack, approximately 1,0005,000 levels of nesting (210 KB input) exhaust the call stack. The exact threshold is environment-dependent (Node.js version, stack size, call stack depth at invocation). Note: the library\u0026#39;s `Parser` (CST phase) uses a stack-based iterative approach and is not affected. Only the compose/resolve phase uses actual call-stack recursion. All three public parsing APIs are affected: `YAML.parse()`, `YAML.parseDocument()`, and `YAML.parseAllDocuments()`. Versions 1.10.3 and 2.8.3 contain a patch."},"fullDescription":{"text":"yaml is a YAML parser and serialiser for JavaScript. Parsing a YAML document with a version of yaml on the 1.x branch prior to 1.10.3 or on the 2.x branch prior to 2.8.3 may throw a \u0026#34;RangeError\u0026#34; due to a Stack Overflow. The node resolution/composition phase uses recursive function calls without a depth bound. An attacker who can supply YAML for parsing can trigger a `RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded` with a small payload (~210 KB). The `RangeError` is not a `YAMLParseError`, so applications that only catch YAML-specific errors will encounter an unexpected exception type. Depending on the host application\u0026#39;s exception handling, this can fail requests or terminate the Node.js process. Flow sequences allow deep nesting with minimal bytes (2 bytes per level: one `[` and one `]`). On the default Node.js stack, approximately 1,0005,000 levels of nesting (210 KB input) exhaust the call stack. The exact threshold is environment-dependent (Node.js version, stack size, call stack depth at invocation). Note: the library\u0026#39;s `Parser` (CST phase) uses a stack-based iterative approach and is not affected. Only the compose/resolve phase uses actual call-stack recursion. All three public parsing APIs are affected: `YAML.parse()`, `YAML.parseDocument()`, and `YAML.parseAllDocuments()`. Versions 1.10.3 and 2.8.3 contain a patch."},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Cve202633532","id":"CVE-2026-33532 (sca)","description":"yaml is a YAML parser and serialiser for JavaScript. Parsing a YAML document with a version of yaml on the 1.x branch prior to 1.10.3 or on the 2.x branch prior to 2.8.3 may throw a \u0026#34;RangeError\u0026#34; due to a Stack Overflow. The node resolution/composition phase uses recursive function calls without a depth bound. An attacker who can supply YAML for parsing can trigger a `RangeError: Maximum call stack size exceeded` with a small payload (~210 KB). The `RangeError` is not a `YAMLParseError`, so applications that only catch YAML-specific errors will encounter an unexpected exception type. Depending on the host application\u0026#39;s exception handling, this can fail requests or terminate the Node.js process. Flow sequences allow deep nesting with minimal bytes (2 bytes per level: one `[` and one `]`). On the default Node.js stack, approximately 1,0005,000 levels of nesting (210 KB input) exhaust the call stack. The exact threshold is environment-dependent (Node.js version, stack size, call stack depth at invocation). Note: the library\u0026#39;s `Parser` (CST phase) uses a stack-based iterative approach and is not affected. Only the compose/resolve phase uses actual call-stack recursion. All three public parsing APIs are affected: `YAML.parse()`, `YAML.parseDocument()`, and `YAML.parseAllDocuments()`. Versions 1.10.3 and 2.8.3 contain a patch.","tags":["security","checkmarx","sca"]}},{"id":"Hardcoded Password in Connection String - 10593680948097685356 (sast)","name":"Hardcoded Password in Connection String","helpUri":"https://checkmarx.com/resource/documents/en/34965-67042-checkmarx-one.html","help":{"text":"The application contains hardcoded connection details, \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;, at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py. This connection string contains a hardcoded password, which is used in test_replace_localhost_with_authentication at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py to connect to a database server with \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;. This can expose the database password, and impede proper password management.\n\n","markdown":"The application contains hardcoded connection details, \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;, at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py. This connection string contains a hardcoded password, which is used in test_replace_localhost_with_authentication at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py to connect to a database server with \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;. This can expose the database password, and impede proper password management.\n\n"},"fullDescription":{"text":"The application contains hardcoded connection details, \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;, at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py. This connection string contains a hardcoded password, which is used in test_replace_localhost_with_authentication at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py to connect to a database server with \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;. This can expose the database password, and impede proper password management.\n\n"},"properties":{"security-severity":"4.0","name":"Hardcoded Password in Connection String","id":"Hardcoded Password in Connection String - 10593680948097685356 (sast)","description":"The application contains hardcoded connection details, \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;, at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py. This connection string contains a hardcoded password, which is used in test_replace_localhost_with_authentication at line 87 of /tests/unit/app_server/test_docker_utils.py to connect to a database server with \u0026#34;http://user:pass@localhost:8080/path\u0026#34;. This can expose the database password, and impede proper 